Instructions
- Define the Task class using the @dataclass decorator from the dataclasses module
- Include fields: id: int, description: str, completed: bool = False, created_at: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.utcnow)
- Implement to_dict(self) -> dict method that returns {'id': self.id, 'description': self.description, 'completed': self.completed, 'created_at': self.created_at.isoformat()}
- Implement from_dict(cls, data: dict) -> Task classmethod that creates a Task from a dictionary, parsing 'created_at' using datetime.fromisoformat() if present
- Add basic validation in __post_init__ or rely on type hints for enforcement
- Use datetime.datetime from the datetime module for timestamp handling
- Ensure the created_at field uses UTC timezone for consistency
- Test edge cases: missing 'completed' field (should default to False), missing 'created_at' (should use current time), invalid datetime format (should raise ValueError)

Deliverable
- A single Python file src/task.py containing the Task dataclass
- The class should be importable and ready to use by other modules (storage, CLI)
- Include proper imports: from dataclasses import dataclass, field; from datetime import datetime

Implementation assumptions (explicit)
- IDs are managed externally (by storage module) and are simple auto-incrementing integers
- All timestamps use UTC without timezone info (naive datetime objects) for simplicity
- No external validation library needed; rely on Python's built-in type system and dataclass features
- The module has no external dependencies beyond Python standard library

Please produce production-ready code for the Task data model consistent with the above requirements.
